  "prompt": "What is the difference between crime and felony and how are they penalized?",
  "response": "Let me explain the differences between crime and felony:\n\nCrime:\n- Broader legal term covering all types of illegal activities\n- Can include minor and serious offenses\n- Divided into different categories:\n1. Misdemeanors (less serious)\n2. Felonies (more serious)\n3. Infractions (minor violations)\n\nFelony:\n- Most serious category of criminal offense\n- Typically involves severe crimes\n- Punishable by imprisonment for more than one year\n- Often involve significant harm or threat to people/property\n\nPenalties for Crimes:\n- Misdemeanors: Usually less than one year in jail, fines\n- Infractions: Typically small fines, no jail time\n- Felonies: Significant prison sentences, substantial fines\n\nFelony Penalties:\n- State prison sentence (1+ years)\n- Higher monetary fines\n- Loss of certain civil rights\n- Potential long-term consequences like:\n1. Difficulty finding employment\n2. Losing voting rights\n3. Restrictions on firearm ownership\n4. Potential deportation for non-citizens\n\nExamples of Felonies:\n- Murder\n- Rape\n- Robbery\n- Aggravated assault\n- Drug trafficking\n- Serious fraud",
